inference:
The lines $4x - 3y = 30$ and $4x - 3y = -10$ are parallel.  The center of the circle must lie on the line that is equidistant from these two lines.  This line is the perpendicular bisector of the segment connecting the points of intersection of the lines with the $x$-axis.

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

A = (15/2,0);
B = (-5/2,0);
C = (A + B)/2;
O = (5/2,-5);

draw((-10,0)--(10,0));
draw((0,-10)--(0,10));
draw((15/2,-10)--(15/2,10),dashed);
draw((-5/2,-10)--(-5/2,10),dashed);
draw((-10,-10)--(10,10),red);
draw((-10,10)--(10,-10),blue);

dot("$A$", A, SE);
dot("$B$", B, SW);
dot("$C$", C, S);
dot("$O$", O, S);
[/asy]

The $x$-intercepts of the lines are $A = \left( \frac{15}{2}, 0 \right)$ and $B = \left( -\frac{5}{2}, 0 \right).$  The midpoint of $\overline{AB}$ is $C = \left( \frac{5}{2}, 0 \right).$  The slope of line $AB$ is 0, so the slope of the perpendicular bisector is undefined.  Hence, the perpendicular bisector is the vertical line $x = \frac{5}{2}.$

The center of the circle lies on the intersection of the lines $x = \frac{5}{2}$ and $2x + y = 0.$  Substituting $x = \frac{5}{2}$ into $2x + y = 0,$ we find $y = -5.$  Therefore, the center of the circle is $\boxed{\left( \frac{5}{2}, -5 \right)}.$

ground_truth:
Note that the lines $4x - 3y = 30$ and $4x - 3y = -10$ are parallel, so the center of the circle lies on the line which is exactly halfway between these lines, which is $4x - 3y = 10.$

[asy]
unitsize(2 cm);

pair A, B;

A = dir(-20);
B = dir(160);

draw(Circle((0,0),1));
draw((A + 1.5*dir(70))--(A - 1.5*dir(70)));
draw((B + 1.5*dir(70))--(B - 1.5*dir(70)));
draw((1.5*dir(70))--(-1.5*dir(70)),dashed);

label("$4x - 3y = -10$", B + 1.5*dir(70), N);
label("$4x - 3y = 30$", A + 1.5*dir(70), N);
label("$4x - 3y = 10$", -1.5*dir(70), S);

dot((0,0));
[/asy]

Solving the system $2x + y = 0$ and $4x - 3y = 10,$ we find $x = 1$ and $y = -2.$  Therefore, the center of the circle is $\boxed{(1,-2)}.$

